{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:03:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:03:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.03,0.12,0.08,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111978"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7187"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94042"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45704"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111978"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 13-hour history of a severe headache that has progressively worsened, especially during physical activity. She describes it as throbbing and occurring on the right side. She feels nauseated and has vomited twice. Before the headache, she experienced visual disturbances described as seeing \u0027light\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has had four previous episodes of similar headaches, which resolved after only two hours after taking 900 mg of aspirin and resting in a dark, quiet room. However, today, the aspirin has not improved her symptoms and her headache persists and is now 8/10 in severity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 22 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Central and peripheral neurological, and otorhinolaryngological examinations are unremarkable. There is no tenderness of the right temporal region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate pharmacological management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rizatriptan","Tramadol","Prochlorperazine","Propranolol","Paracetamol/Codeine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a long-lasting (\u0026gt; 12-hour) unilateral throbbing headache associated with nausea and vomiting, and a history of similar headache episodes that are sensitive to light and sounds. These findings suggest that this patient has a migraine. Migraine is one of the most common forms of headache, and it significantly affects the quality of life of a patient. It is thought to occur because of the neurogenic inflammation of the meningeal vasculature and sensitisation of the nociceptive pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENSAIDs are typically first-line treatment for acute migraine attacks. Since this patient has already tried aspirin without relief, as per the Therapeutic Guidelines, the next step in management would be rehydrating the patient and adding a dopamine antagonist, such as metoclopramide, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprochlorperazine\u003C/strong\u003E, or chlorpromazine, to the anti-inflammatory medication. \u003Cstrong\u003EProchlorperazine\u003C/strong\u003E acts not only to treat the associated nausea and vomiting but also has analgesic properties for migraine headaches and improves the efficacy of NSAIDs by improving absorption. It works by blocking dopamine receptors in the chemoreceptor trigger zone and has been shown to be effective in reducing migraine pain intensity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERizatriptan\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is an abortive treatment for acute migraine attacks, most effective if given soon after the onset of the headache (not before, during the aura, or after the headache has been severe). It acts as a selective agonist for serotonin receptors, leading to vasoconstriction of intracranial blood vessels and inhibition of pro-inflammatory neuropeptide release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note, for patients with intractable migraine, defined as migrainous headache lasting \u0026gt;72 hours that has not responded to anti-inflammatories, a dopamine antagonist and rehydration, then as per the Therapeutic Guidelines, subcutaneous sumatriptan or IM ketorolac are the next line options that could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETramadol\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid analgesic that is not typically recommended for migraine management due to the risk of medication overuse headache and potential for dependency. It would not be an appropriate choice in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker used for migraine prophylaxis, not for acute management, making it unsuitable for this scenario where the patient requires immediate relief from an ongoing migraine attack.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol and codeine \u003C/strong\u003E(Panadeine forte), which may provide some relief but is not a preferred treatment for migraines due to the risk of medication overuse headache and potential for dependency. Additionally, opioids are generally avoided in migraine management when other options are available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dopamine antagonists are effective for acute migraine attacks by relieving nausea and vomiting while also providing analgesic effects.","NSAIDs are first-line treatment for acute migraine, with dopamine antagonists commonly used as second-line therapy in Australian emergency departments."],"references":["Migraine [updated 2019 Jan]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed March 7, 2024. https://www-tg-org-au.elibrary.jcu.edu.au","Lanfranco Pellesi, Thien Phu Do, Hougaard A. Pharmacological management of migraine: current strategies and future directions. Expert Opinion on Pharmacotherapy. 2024 Apr 12;25(6):673\u201383.","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Headache. Available at \u003Chttps://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/headache/\u003E","Wijeratne T, Kuan WS, Kelly AM, Chu KH, Kinnear FB, Keijzers G, Body R, Karamercan MA, Klim S, Kamona S, Graham CA, Roberts T, Horner D, Laribi S; on behalf HEAD study group. Migraine in the Emergency Department: A Prospective Multinational Study of Patient Characteristics, Management, and Outcomes. Neuroepidemiology. 2022;56(1):32-40. doi: 10.1159/000520548. Epub 2022 Jan 12. PMID: 35021181. \u003Chttps://www.westernhealth.org.au/EducationandResearch/Research_Groups/JECEMR/Documents/HEAD/HEAD%204%20_%20Migraine.pdf\u003E","Emergency Care Institute. Agency for Clinical Innovation. NSW Health. Available at \u003Chttps://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/tools/neurology/headache/migraine \u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94042"}},"question":{"